nodes.def: A partial duplication, depending on severity leading to a broad or bifid appearance, affecting one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand. As opposed to a complete duplication there is still a variable degree of fusion between the duplicated bones.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the hallux
Bullet-shaped distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Short and wide distal phalanges that taper distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved distal phalanges of the hand
Osteolytic defects of the distal phalanges of the hand
Patchy sclerosis of distal phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of the distal phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Broad middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Increased width of the middle phalanx of finger.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: Any of the middle phalanges with short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved middle phalanges of the hand
Osteolytic defects of the middle phalanges of the hand
Patchy sclerosis of middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Uneven (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the hand.

nodes.label: Symphalangism of middle phalanx of finger
nodes.def: Fusion of a middle phalanx of a finger with another bone.

nodes.label: Triangular shaped middle phalanges of the hand
Curved proximal phalanges of the hand
Triangular shaped proximal phalanges of the hand
Triangular shaped distal phalanges of the hand
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
Duplication of the phalanges of the 2nd toe
nodes.def: Partial or complete duplication of a phalanx of second toe.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 3rd toe
Abnormality of the distal phalanx of the 3rd toe
Abnormality of the middle phalanx of the 3rd toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 4th toe
Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the phalanges of the 5th toe
Polydactyly
nodes.def: A congenital anomaly characterized by the presence of supernumerary fingers or toes.

nodes.label: Irregular epiphyses
nodes.def: An alteration of the normally smooth contour of the epiphysis leading to an irregular appearance.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses
nodes.def: Reduction in the size or volume of epiphyses.

nodes.label: Premature epimetaphyseal fusion
nodes.def: Stop of growth at the epiphyseal plate the hyaline cartilage plate in the metaphysis at each end of a long bone, at an earlier than normal age, resulting in growth arrest and shortening of the involved bone.

nodes.label: Cutaneous syndactyly of toes
nodes.def: A soft tissue continuity in the anteroposterior axis between adjacent foot digits that involves at least half of the proximodistal length of one of the two involved digits; or, a soft tissue continuity in the A/P axis between two digits of the foot that does not meet the prior objective criteria.

nodes.label: Aplasia of the distal phalanges of the toes
nodes.def: Absence of the distal phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Abnormal zygomatic bone morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the zygomatic bone.

nodes.label: EEG with generalized slow activity
nodes.def: Diffuse slowing of cerebral electrical activity recorded along the scalp by electroencephalography (EEG).

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating long-chain fatty-acid concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a long-chain fatty acid in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal circulating fatty-acid anion concentration
nodes.def: Any deviation from the normal concentration of a fatty acid anion in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormality of lipoprotein cholesterol concentration
nodes.def: An abnormal increase or decrease in the level of lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the intrinsic pathway
nodes.def: An abnormality of the intrinsic pathway (also known as the contact activation pathway) of the coagulation cascade.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal cortex morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the cortex of the kidney.

nodes.label: Abnormal intervertebral disk morphology
nodes.def: Any structural abnormality of the intervertebral disk.

nodes.label: EEG with focal spikes
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec.

nodes.label: EEG with focal spike waves
nodes.def: EEG with focal sharp transient waves of a duration less than 80 msec followed by a slow wave.

nodes.label: Abnormal pupillary function
nodes.def: A functional abnormality of the pupil.

nodes.label: Opacification of the corneal stroma
nodes.def: Reduced transparency of the stroma of cornea.

nodes.label: Abnormality of macular pigmentation
nodes.def: Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation.

nodes.label: Ichthyosis
nodes.def: An abnormality of the skin characterized the presence of excessive amounts of dry surface scales on the skin resulting from an abnormality of keratinization.

nodes.label: Abnormal branching pattern of the aortic arch
nodes.def: A deviance from the norm of the origin or course of the right brachiocephalic artery, the left common carotid artery, the left subclavian artery or the proximal vertebral arteries.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the femoral head and neck
Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum.

nodes.label: Mixed hypo- and hyperpigmentation of the skin
Increased adipose tissue
nodes.def: An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell).

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the metacarpal epiphyses
nodes.def: Fragmented appearance of the epiphyses of the metacarpals.

nodes.label: Metacarpal pseudoepiphysis
nodes.def: A pseudoepiphysis is a secondary ossification center distinct from the normal epiphysis. The normal metacarpal epiphyses are located at the distal ends of the metacarpal bones. Accessory epiphyses (which are also known as pseudoepiphyses) can also occasionally be observed at the proximal ends of the metacarpals, usually involving the 2nd metacarpal bone.

nodes.label: Abnormal urine hormone level
nodes.def: An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the urine.

nodes.label: Abnormal respiratory system morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the respiratory system.

nodes.label: Absent epiphyses of the toes
nodes.def: Absence of the epiphyses of the phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the toes
Epiphyseal stippling of toe phalanges
nodes.def: The presence of abnormal punctate (speckled, dot-like) calcifications in the epiphyses of phalanges of the toes.

nodes.label: Broad distal phalanx of the toes
nodes.def: Increased width of the distal phalanx of toe of one or more toes.

nodes.label: Curved distal toe phalanx
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight form of one or more distal toe phalanges.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of distal toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the distal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the middle phalanges of the toes
Patchy sclerosis of middle phalanx of toe
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the middle phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Broad proximal phalanx of toe
nodes.def: An increase in width of one ore more proximal toe phalanges.

nodes.label: Bullet-shaped proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: An abnormal morphology of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes, with a short and wide phalanx that tapers distally. Bullet-shaped phalanges lack the normal diaphyseal constriction.

nodes.label: Curved proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: A deviation from the normal straight shape of a proximal phalanx of one or more toes.

nodes.label: Patchy sclerosis of proximal toe phalanx
nodes.def: Patchy (irregular) increase in bone density of one or more of the proximal phalanges of the toes. This can take on many forms depending on severity and distribution as can be seen on x-rays.

nodes.label: Absent epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the distal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Enlarged epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the distal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Triangular epiphyses of the distal phalanges of the hand
Absent epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the middle phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Enlarged epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the middle phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Triangular epiphyses of the middle phalanges of the hand
Absent epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Bracket epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: An abnormality of the proximal phalanges of the hand in which the epiphysis surrounds a phalangeal bone, having a bracket-like form and reaching from the proximal side of a phalanx to the distal side.

nodes.label: Cone-shaped epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Fragmentation of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Irregular epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Pseudoepiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
nodes.def: A secondary ossification center in the proximal phalanges of the hand that is distinct from the normal epiphysis that does not contribute to the longitudinal growth of a tubular bone.

nodes.label: Small epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Stippling of the epiphyses of the proximal phalanges of the hand
Abnormal salivary gland morphology
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva.

nodes.label: Abnormal myelination
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the process by which myelin sheaths are formed and maintained around neurons.

nodes.label: Abnormal platelet function
nodes.def: Any anomaly in the function of thrombocytes.

nodes.label: Hemorrhage of the eye
nodes.def: Bleeding from vessels of the various tissues of the eye.

nodes.label: Abnormal sperm morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of sperm.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of the vestibule of the inner ear
nodes.def: A morphological abnormality of the vestibule, the central part of the osseous labyrinth that is situated medial to the tympanic cavity, behind the cochlea, and in front of the semicircular canals.

nodes.label: Abnormal inner ear morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the internal part of the ear.

nodes.label: Age of death
nodes.def: The age group when the cessation of life happens.

nodes.label: Abnormal lacrimal punctum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the lacrimal punctum, an opening on the eyelid close to the medial canthus that drains tears from the conjunctival sac into the lacrimal duct in the same eyelid.

nodes.label: Abnormal small intestinal mucosa morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the mucous lining of the small intestine.

nodes.label: Abnormal lymph-node germinal center morphology
nodes.def: Any phenotypic abnormality of germinal centers of a lymph node.

nodes.label: Incomitant strabismus
nodes.def: Strabismus in which the angle of deviation differs depending upon the direction of gaze or according to which eye is fixing, associated with: (i) defective movement of the eye, (ii) asymmetrical accommodative effort.

nodes.label: Abnormal B cell subset distribution
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of any B cell subpopulation, measured as percentage of total CD19+ or CD20+ B cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

nodes.label: Anterior chamber cells
nodes.def: Tiny deposits corresponding to cells floating in the anterior chamber of the eye. This appearance is typically associated with intraocular inflammation leading to breakdown of the blood-aqueous barrier and resulting in an increase in the number of cells and in the aqueous humor. Grading (SUN Working Group) is performed by estimating the number of cells in a 1 mm by 1 mm slit beam field, employing adequate light intensity and magnification on a slit lamp.

nodes.label: Cholangitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the biliary ductal system, affecting the intrahepatic or extrahepatic portions, or both.

nodes.label: Abnormal vascular physiology
nodes.def: Abnormality of vascular function.

nodes.label: Weakness of facial musculature
nodes.def: Reduced strength of one or more muscles innervated by the facial nerve (the seventh cranial nerve).

nodes.label: Abnormal ocular adnexa morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the adjacent structures (i.e., adnexa) of the eye, defined as the lacrimal apparatus, the extraocular muscles and the eyelids, eyelashes, eyebrows and the conjunctiva.

nodes.label: Abnormal pulmonary vein morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the structure of the pulmonary veins.

nodes.label: Impairment of activities of daily living
nodes.def: Difficulty in performing one or more activities normally performed every day, such as eating, bathing, dressing, grooming, work, homemaking, and leisure.

nodes.label: Abnormal Bowman capsule morphology
nodes.def: A structural anomaly of the double-walled capsule (Bowman capsule) that opens into a renal tubule.

nodes.label: Abnormal urine cytology
nodes.def: An anomalous finding in the examination of the urine for cells.

nodes.label: Cough
nodes.def: A sudden, audible expulsion of air from the lungs through a partially closed glottis, preceded by inhalation.

nodes.label: Pulmonary opacity
nodes.def: Opacity refers to any area that preferentially attenuates the x-ray beam and therefore appears more opaque than the surrounding area. It is a nonspecific term that does not indicate the size or pathologic nature of the abnormality.

nodes.label: Impairment in personality functioning
nodes.def: A maladaptive personality trait characterized by moderate or greater impairment in personality (self /interpersonal) functioning.

nodes.label: Orbital cleft
nodes.def: A facial cleft characterized by involvement of the orbit.

nodes.label: Abnormal P wave
nodes.def: Any anomaly of the P wave of the EKG, which results from atrial depolarization. The P wave occurs when the sinoatrial node creates an action potential that depolarizes the atria.

nodes.label: Atherosclerotic lesion
nodes.def: A lesion associated with atherosclerosis, a multifactorial and multipart progressive disease manifested by the focal development within the arterial wall of lesions, that ranges from the development of a fatty streak, plaque progression, and plaque disruption. Atherosclerotic lesions demonstrate consistent morphological characteristics, which indicate that each type may stabilize temporarily or permanently and that progression to the next type may require an additional stimulus.

nodes.label: Opportunistic infection
nodes.def: An infection that is caused by a pathogen that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such pathogens take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

nodes.label: Abnormal ear physiology
nodes.def: Any functional anomaly of the ear.

nodes.label: Compensatory head posture
nodes.def: A compensatory head posture occurs when the head is deviated out of the normal primary straight head position in order to compensate for an ocular problem.

nodes.label: Lymphangiectasis
nodes.def: Dilation of the lymphatic vessels, the basic process that may result in the formation of a lymphangioma.

nodes.label: Bloodstream infectious agent
nodes.def: The presence of an infectious agent in the blood circulation.

nodes.label: Abnormal cranial nerve physiology
nodes.def: A functional abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem.

nodes.label: Abnormal portal venous system morphology
nodes.def: Any structural anomaly of the portal venous system, which comprises all of the veins draining the abdominal part of the digestive tract, including the lower esophagus but excluding the lower anal canal. The portal vein conveys blood from viscera and ramifies like an artery at the liver, ending at the sinusoids. Tributaries of the portal vein, which make up the portal venous system, are the splenic, superior mesenteric, left gastric, right gastric, paraumbilical, and cystic veins.

nodes.label: Heterotropia
nodes.def: Manifest deviation of the visual axes not controlled by fusion.

nodes.label: Abnormal sputum
nodes.def: Abnormal appearance of material expectorated (coughed up) from the respiratory system and that is composed of mucus but may contain other substances such as pus, blood, microorganisms, and fibrin.

nodes.label: Subcortical heterotopia
nodes.def: A form of heterotopia were the mislocalized gray matter is located deep within the white matter.

nodes.label: Focal aware non-motor seizure
nodes.def: A focal non-motor seizure in which awareness is retained throughout the seizure.

nodes.label: Focal impaired awareness non-motor seizure
nodes.def: A focal non-motor seizure characterized by impaired awareness at some point during the seizure.

nodes.label: Abnormal shoulder physiology
nodes.def: Anopmalous function of the shoulder. The shoulder is a ball-and-socket joint that is made up of humerus, scapula and clavicle, which are connected by the sternoclavicular joint (SC), the acromioclavicular joint (AC), the glenohumeral joint (GH), and the scapulothoracic joint (ST). The GH, AC and SC joints link the upper extremity to the axial skeleton at the thorax and enable movement at the shoulder joint: flexion, extension, and rotation of the arm.

nodes.label: Abnormal pulmonary alveolar system morphology
nodes.def: A structural abnormality of the pulmonary acinus, alveolar parenchyma, or alveoli.

nodes.label: Acute phase response
nodes.def: Presence of one or more manifestations of the acute phase response. Acute phase proteins (APP) are blood proteins primarily synthesized by hepatocytes as part of the acute phase response (APR). The APR is part of the early-defense or innate immune system, which is triggered by different stimuli including trauma, infection, stress, neoplasia, and inflammation. The APR results in a complex systemic reaction with the goal of reestablishing homeostasis and promoting healing.

nodes.label: Extractable nuclear antigen positivity
nodes.def: The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against extractable nuclear components that are referred to as extractable because they can be extracted from cell nuclei with saline solution.

nodes.label: Addictive substance use
nodes.def: Chronic compulsive drug seeking and continued use despite harmful consequences.

nodes.label: Abnormal lymphocyte count
nodes.def: Any abnormality in the total number of lymphocytes in the blood.

nodes.label: Abnormal CSF pterin concentration
nodes.def: Abnormal concentration of a pterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the central nervous system
nodes.def: A neoplasm of the central nervous system.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the eye
nodes.def: A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the eye.

nodes.label: Muscle fiber cytoplasmatic inclusion bodies
nodes.def: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells. Inclusion bodies are aggregates (deposits) or stainable material, usually misfolded proteins.

nodes.label: Juvenile aseptic necrosis
nodes.def: Juvenile aseptic necrosis comprises a group of orthopedic diseases characterized by interruption of the blood supply of a bone, followed by localized bony necrosis most often of the epiphyses of bones of children or teenagers.

nodes.label: Immunologic hypersensitivity
nodes.def: Immunological states where the immune system produces harmful responses upon reexposure to sensitizing antigens.

nodes.label: Upper-limb joint contracture
nodes.def: A limitation in the passive range of motion of a joint of the upper limb resulting from loss of elasticity in the periarticular tissues owing to structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules or skin.

nodes.label: Rhabdoid tumor
nodes.def: Rhabdoid tumors are rare aggressive malignancies in infants and young children with a poor prognosis. The most common anatomic localizations are the central nervous system, the kidneys, and other soft tissues.

nodes.label: Abnormal liver metabolite concentration
nodes.def: The concentration of a metabolite in the liver is above or below the limits of normal.

nodes.label: Shoulder contracture
nodes.def: Lack of full passive range of motion (restrictions in flexion, extension, or other movements) of the shoulder joint resulting from structural changes of non-bony tissues, such as muscles, tendons, ligaments, joint capsules and/or skin.

nodes.label: Abnormality of vitamin metabolism
nodes.def: An anomaly in the metabolism of a vitamin.

nodes.label: Gastrointestinal eosinophilia
nodes.def: Eosinophilic infiltration of one or more gastrointestinal organs. Gastrointestinal eosinophilia is a broad term for abnormal eosinophil accumulation in the GI tract, involving many different disease identities. These diseases include primary eosinophil associated gastrointestinal diseases, gastrointestinal eosinophilia in HES and all gastrointestinal eosinophilic states associated with known causes. Each of these diseases has its unique features but there is no absolute boundary between them.

nodes.label: Opportunistic fungal infection
nodes.def: An infection that is caused by a fungus that would generally not be able to cause an infection in a host with a normal immune system. Such fungi take advantage of the opportunity, so to speak, that is provided by a weakened immune system.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the large intestine
nodes.def: The presence of a neoplasm of the large intestine.

nodes.label: Abnormal palm morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the palm, that is, of the front of the hand.

nodes.label: Abnormality of globe location
nodes.def: An abnormality in the placement of the ocular globe (eyeball).

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 2nd finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the second finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 3rd finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the third finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 4th finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fourth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of 5th finger phalanx
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more phalanges of the fifth finger. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Sclerosis of proximal phalanx of toe
nodes.def: An elevation in bone density in one or more proximal phalanges of the toes. Sclerosis is normally detected on a radiograph as an area of increased opacity.

nodes.label: Abnormal memory CD8+ T cell proportion
nodes.def: Abnormal increase or decrease of the memory CD8+ T cell subpopulation, commonly characterized as CD45RA-, CD45RO+, or CD27-, measured as percentage of total CD8+ T cells in the blood, compared to a reference range for a given sex and age-group.

nodes.label: Abnormality of musculature of soft palate
nodes.def: An abnormality of one or more of the five muscles of the soft palate.

nodes.label: Small joint hypermobilty
nodes.def:
The capability that a small joint (or a group of joints) has to move, passively and/or actively, beyond normal limits along physiological axes. Small joints include metacarpophalangeal joints, proximal interphalangeal joints, 
second to fifth metatarsophalangeal joints, and wrists.

nodes.label: Bloodstream pathogen-specific antibody positivity
nodes.def: Positive serology for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining serum for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

nodes.label: Sputum infectious agent
nodes.def: The presence of an infectious agent in the sputum, as characterized by sputum culture or other investigation.

nodes.label: Brain localization
nodes.def: The pattern by which a phenotype is localized to or predominant in a part of the brain.

nodes.label: CSF pathogen-specific antibody positivity
nodes.def: Positive serology in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for a exposure to an infectious agent (i.e., examining CSF for the presence of pathogen-specific antibodies).

nodes.label: Food allergy
nodes.def: Primary food allergies primarily occur as a result (most likely) of gastrointestinal sensitization to predominantly stable food allergens (glycoproteins). A secondary food allergy develops after primary sensitization to airborne allergens (e. g., pollen allergens) with subsequent reactions (due to cross-reactivity) to structurally related often labile allergens in (plant) foods.

nodes.label: Amplification of social interactions
nodes.def: A increase in the tendency of a person to seek or maintain social connections or interactions with others compared to previous norms for an individual.

nodes.label: Abnormal movement during sleep
nodes.def: Periodic Limb Movement Disorder, also known as Sleep-Related Myoclonus Syndrome or Nocturnal Myoclonus Syndrome, refers to the periodic and stereotypic movements of the legs or upper limbs during sleep.

nodes.label: Abnormal experience of reality
nodes.def: Subjective phenomena or perceptions that deviate from what is considered correct or are outside the range of normal human experiences.

nodes.label: Short metatarsal
nodes.def: Diminished length of a metatarsal bone, with resultant proximal displacement of the associated toe.

nodes.label: Lupus nephritis
nodes.def: Lupus nephritis is a type of glomerulonephritis that constitutes one of the most severe organ manifestations of systemic lupus erythematosus. Lupus nephritis is subclassified in six distinct classes, that represent different manifestations and severities of renal involvement and guide the therapeutic management.

nodes.label: Blistering by anatomical location
nodes.def: Blistering (presence of multiple fluid filled blisters) categorized according to the body site where they occur.

nodes.label: Abnormal epidermis stratum granulosum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormal structure of the stratum granulosum, which is is a thin layer of cells in the epidermis lying above the stratum spinosum and below the stratum corneum.

nodes.label: Abnormal renal vascular morphology
nodes.def: Anomalous structure of a blood vessel in the kidney.

nodes.label: Frequency
nodes.def: Class to represent frequency of phenotypic abnormalities within a patient cohort.

nodes.label: Glomerular deposits
nodes.def: An abnormal accumulation of protein in the glomerulus.

nodes.label: Involuntary vocalization
nodes.def: Production of sound done without will or conscious control. Involuntary vocalizations include tics, stereotypies vocalizations as part of dystonia or chorea, continuous vocalizing behaviors such as groaning or grunting, pathological laughter and crying, and others. These vocalizations are not recognized as socially or culturally appropriate.

nodes.label: Fractured distal finger phalanx
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the distal phalanx of manus.

nodes.label: Toe phalanx fracture
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the phalanx of pes.

nodes.label: Fractured finger phalanx
nodes.def: A partial or complete breakage of the phalanx of a finger.

nodes.label: Increased fecal porphyrin
nodes.def: Abnormally high concentration of fecal porphyrins in feces.

nodes.label: Abnormal glial cell morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the glia cell.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the tonsils
nodes.def: An abnormality of the tonsils.

nodes.label: Neoplasm of the small intestine
nodes.def: The presence of a neoplasm of the small intestine.

nodes.label: Abnormal morphology of female internal genitalia
nodes.def: An abnormality of the female internal genitalia.

nodes.label: Ambiguous genitalia
nodes.def: A genital phenotype that is not clearly assignable to a single gender. Ambiguous genitalia can be evaluated using the Prader scale: Prader 0: Normal female external genitalia. Prader 1: Female external genitalia with clitoromegaly. Prader 2: Clitoromegaly with partial labial fusion forming a funnel-shaped urogenital sinus. Prader 3: Increased phallic enlargement. Complete labioscrotal fusion forming a urogenital sinus with a single opening. Prader 4: Complete scrotal fusion with urogenital opening at the base or on the shaft of the phallus. Prader 5: Normal male external genitalia. The diagnosis of ambiguous genitalia is made for Prader 1-4.

nodes.label: Vesicoureteral reflux
nodes.def: Abnormal (retrograde) movement of urine from the bladder into ureters or kidneys related to inadequacy of the valvular mechanism at the ureterovesicular junction or other causes.

nodes.label: Tall stature
nodes.def: A height above that which is expected according to age and gender norms.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the genitourinary system
nodes.def: The presence of any abnormality of the genitourinary system.

nodes.label: Hypogonadism
nodes.def: A decreased functionality of the gonad.

nodes.label: Cleft soft palate
nodes.def: Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency.

nodes.label: Abnormal oral frenulum morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity.

nodes.label: Oral cavity telangiectasia
nodes.def: Presence of telangiectases in the oral cavity.

nodes.label: Hydrocephalus
nodes.def: Hydrocephalus is an active distension of the ventricular system of the brain resulting from inadequate passage of CSF from its point of production within the cerebral ventricles to its point of absorption into the systemic circulation.

nodes.label: Facial asymmetry
nodes.def: An abnormal difference between the left and right sides of the face.

nodes.label: Retinal detachment
nodes.def: Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium.

nodes.label: Myopia
nodes.def: An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects nearby clearly, while objects in the distance appear blurry.

nodes.label: Retinal degeneration
nodes.def: A nonspecific term denoting degeneration of the retinal pigment epithelium and/or retinal photoreceptor cells.

nodes.label: Abnormal uvea morphology
nodes.def: An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball.

nodes.label: Ophthalmoparesis
nodes.def: Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the frontal hairline
nodes.def: An anomaly in the placement or shape of the hairline (trichion) on the forehead, that is, the border between skin on the forehead that has head hair and that does not.

nodes.label: Periodontitis
nodes.def: Inflammation of the periodontium.

nodes.label: Motor stereotypy
nodes.def: Use of the same abnormal action in response to certain triggers or at random. They may be used as a way to regulate one's internal state but must otherwise have no apparent functional purpose.

nodes.label: Anxiety
nodes.def: Intense feelings of nervousness, tension, or panic often arise in response to interpersonal stresses. There is worry about the negative effects of past unpleasant experiences and future negative possibilities. Individuals may feel fearful, apprehensive, or threatened by uncertainty, and they may also have fears of falling apart or losing control.

nodes.label: Delayed speech and language development
nodes.def: A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the diaphragm
nodes.def: Any abnormality of the diaphragm, the sheet of skeletal muscle that separates the thoracic cavity from the abdominal cavity.

nodes.label: Oligozoospermia
nodes.def: Reduced count of spermatozoa in the semen, defined as a sperm count below 20 million per milliliter semen.

nodes.label: Hyperthyroidism
nodes.def: An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3).

nodes.label: Atypical scarring of skin
nodes.def: Atypically scarred skin .

nodes.label: Cutaneous photosensitivity
nodes.def: An increased sensitivity of the skin to light. Photosensitivity may result in a rash upon exposure to the sun (which is known as photodermatosis). Photosensitivity can be diagnosed by phototests in which light is shone on small areas of skin.

nodes.label: Melanocytic nevus
nodes.def: A oval and round, colored (usually medium-to dark brown, reddish brown, or flesh colored) lesion. Typically, a melanocytic nevus is less than 6 mm in diameter, but may be much smaller or larger.

nodes.label: Multiple lipomas
nodes.def: The presence of multiple lipomas (a type of benign tissue made of fatty tissue).

nodes.label: Angiokeratoma
nodes.def: Angiokeratomas are hyperkeratotic papules that are characterized histologically by superficial ectatic (i.e., dilated) blood vessels with epidermal proliferation. Clinically, angiokeratoma presents as a small, raised, dark-red spot.

nodes.label: Prominent superficial veins
nodes.def: A condition in which superficial veins (i.e., veins just under the skin) are more conspicuous or noticeable than normal.

nodes.label: Constriction of peripheral visual field
nodes.def: An absolute or relative decrease in retinal sensitivity extending from edge (periphery) of the visual field in a concentric pattern. The visual field is the area that is perceived simultaneously by a fixating eye.

nodes.label: Retinal exudate
nodes.def: Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina.

nodes.label: Postaxial hand polydactyly
nodes.def: Supernumerary digits located at the ulnar side of the hand (that is, on the side with the fifth finger).

nodes.label: Mental deterioration
nodes.def: Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults.

nodes.label: Holoprosencephaly
nodes.def: Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles.

nodes.label: Cholestasis
nodes.def: Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts.

nodes.label: Abnormality of the shoulder girdle musculature
